registry/assessments/a5-nl.json:29:  "scope_note": "Every number below is index-bound to: kernel state kernel-v0 (8209cada) + code-v0 (01009b1f) + code-world-v0 (b8a8a50a) + code-axioms-v0 (dc930b4f) as frozen; ONE deterministic front-end build (mapper a1-hybrid policy sha e13dc838, one identifier gazetteer, one frozen frame rule set, front-end sha 59037776 pinned BEFORE any EVAL phrasing existed); ONE blind agent-authored held-out phrasing set (K=1 per query, section-5 blind protocol); the parents' frozen eval/stores byte-identical, the kot_code desugar layer byte-identical to the parent pin; the engine behaviourally parent-perfect on the parent eval, re-verified IN-RUN by gate G2 (ASM-0147); ONE 15-file Python snapshot corpus. Rungs measured: R0 (no host model, no GPU). Scored slice: the full 855 frozen covered queries (a5-nl is NOT re-scoped — FK-NLB-10 is l3a-only). REGISTERED HONESTY NOTE (frozen): on the code vertical the mapper's lexicon leg is THIN — the seven relational ops are carried by frame keywords + identifier gazetteer, and the mapper's concept mapping decides only the instance-of concept slot; a5-nl therefore stresses frame + entity-linking, l3a-parse stresses lexicon mapping. Each licenses only its vertical.",
registry/assessments/a5-nl.json:32:  "_surprise_note": "No registered surprise-prior / claim.md exists for a5-nl, so no surprise-* tag is licensed. Informally, and quotable only as planning-value context: the primary planning value was 0.95; measured 0.416 (356/855) undershot it by a wide margin, a decisive FAIL. The genuinely notable feature — not a registered surprise — is that a5-nl trips the S2 dangerous-wrong KILL that its sibling l3a-parse does NOT (43/855 vs 8/527), located almost entirely in the containment/definition-location families; the design's own honesty note (frame + entity-linking is the stressed stage here) predicted the code vertical's weak seat is the frame layer, and the wrong-answer concentration confirms exactly that stage.",
registry/assessments/a5-nl.json:35:    "headline": "a5-nl is a DECISIVE, INSTRUMENT-VALID coverage FAIL of the deterministic NL front-end on the code vertical that ADDITIONALLY breaks the fail-closed contract — the DANGEROUS kind of failure, and the load-bearing contrast with its family/world sibling. Machinery leg [MEASURED]: over the SAME frozen eval queries, the gold-parse arm reproduced the parent-perfect result in-run (gold_replication_identical true; 855/855) and the deranged-lexicon control collapsed to 0.0 (G5) — the engine, kot_code desugaring, renderer, and scorer all work; the closed kot-query-code/1 grammar is decidable exactly as banked. NL-boundary leg [MEASURED]: routed through the deterministic a1-hybrid front-end, the same queries reach a correct, engine-answered, exact result on only 356 of 855 blind NL phrasings = 41.6% (one-sided Wilson 95% UB 0.4443 vs the frozen 0.90 retention bar), so the FAIL leg (UB <= 0.90) fires cleanly — the NL boundary eats roughly 58% of the rung. Fail-closed leg [MEASURED]: the S2 dangerous-wrong-answer KILL ALSO fired independently — covered wrong 43/855 = 5.0% (Wilson LB 0.0394 >= the 0.02 kill floor, 43 >= the 24-item fire threshold), so a5-nl has TWO independent FAIL causes, not one. The wrong answers are concentrated exactly where the design flagged the weak seat: contained-in (24/201 wrong) and where-defined (18/201 wrong) — the directional containment/definition-location families where the frame layer's ROLE_DIR direction table mis-parses 'what contains X' vs 'what X contains' into a valid-but-WRONG location answered with provenance attached. The call-graph families, by contrast, parse near-ceiling (callers-of 69/74, callees-of 60/73). Notably the CONTROL fail-closed is good (S1: 104/106 acceptable-refusal, holm_s1_pass true) — a5-nl refuses out-of-scope queries well but MIS-ANSWERS in-scope covered queries, the opposite profile from l3a-parse (which mis-handles some controls but keeps covered mis-parses safe). Net for the correctness thesis: the deterministic training-free NL front-end does NOT survive the natural-language boundary on the code vertical AND breaks its safety contract there; the frozen kill routes verbatim — 'fix the parser stage, not the narrative, and spend nothing on GPU for this leg' — with the frame stage indicted (frame-miss 468 dominant).",
registry/assessments/a5-nl.json:39:    "scope_envelope": "The envelope is the frozen extrapolation_envelope_verbatim, restated honestly. WHAT THIS FAIL ESTABLISHES: on the full 855-query frozen slice of the closed kot-query-code/1 grammar (code vertical, one 15-file Python snapshot), the ONE pinned deterministic a1-hybrid front-end build does not retain 90% of gold-parse covered exactness from THESE blind held-out NL phrasings AND breaks the fail-closed contract (wrong-answer rate above the 0.02 dangerous floor). It indicts the frame stage. WHAT IT DOES NOT GENERALIZE TO: (a) NO other mapper, gazetteer, or frame build — this is an a1-hybrid-specific result and the pre-declared successor (FK-NLB-3) is an LLM-assisted parser, a DIFFERENT front-end class the kill routes investment to; (b) NO other codebase or programming language, NO other phrasing distribution, NO natural-user-distribution robustness claim (phrasings agent-authored under a blind protocol); NO extraction-soundness claim w.r.t. runtime semantics (ASM-0009 unchanged); (c) NO LLM-comparative accuracy or cost claim (a5-llm / a5-llm-frontier), NO statement about kernel usefulness to any model; (d) NO cross-vertical conjunction — l3a-parse licenses the family/world vertical separately, and its fail-closed OUTCOME is the OPPOSITE (its S2 KILL did not fire), so the safety reading must stay strictly per-vertical; (e) it does NOT indict the kernel, the engine, or the closed grammar — the gold path replicates perfectly (855/855), so this is a boundary/front-end result, not a decidability result. A decisive FAIL is not softened (41.6% with UB 0.44, plus a fired safety kill), and a scoped FAIL is not over-generalized (it kills the a1-hybrid front-end at this slice, not the NL boundary in principle).",
registry/assessments/a5-nl.json:45:      "[MEASURED] The front-end BREAKS the fail-closed contract on the code vertical: covered wrong 43/855 = 5.0% (Wilson LB 0.0394 >= 0.02), the S2 dangerous-wrong KILL fired independently. Wrong answers concentrate in the directional containment/definition-location families (contained-in 24, where-defined 18, contains 1) — the frame-layer ROLE_DIR direction table mis-parses orientation into a real-but-wrong answer with provenance attached.",
registry/assessments/a5-nl.json:47:      "[MEASURED] Control fail-closed is GOOD in isolation (S1: 104/106 = 98.1% acceptable-refusal, holm_s1_pass true) — a5-nl refuses out-of-scope queries well; its safety failure is on the COVERED slice, the opposite profile from l3a-parse. This asymmetry (good controls, dangerous covered) is itself the diagnostic that the frame direction table, not entity-linking, is the failing sub-stage.",
registry/assessments/a5-nl.json:53:      "[ENVELOPE-BOUND] NO cross-vertical conjunction. l3a-parse licenses the family/world vertical separately and its S2 KILL did NOT fire — so a5-nl's fail-closed break is a CODE-VERTICAL-SPECIFIC safety result. Reading the pair as one 'NL boundary FAIL' is legitimate only at the DIRECTION level (both fail the 0.90 bar); the safety reading must stay per-vertical (l3a safe, a5 dangerous).",
registry/assessments/a5-nl.json:54:      "[DESIGN-BOUND] This FAIL does NOT indict the kernel content, the engine, or the closed grammar's decidability — all of which the gold-replication arm confirms sound (855/855). It also does NOT retract the a5-llm engine-vs-LLM PASS: that was a substrate comparison over gold-parsed formal inputs; a5-nl carries the NL/parse confound a5-llm was pre-registered not to close, and now measures it as a FAIL. The engine still beats the LLM cells on FORMAL inputs; it just cannot be reached from NL through this deterministic front-end.",
registry/assessments/a5-nl.json:55:      "[BINDING-NOTE — safety] The a5-nl fail-closed break is a binding SAFETY caveat for any code-vertical NL story (ASM-0720): a deterministic front-end on the code vertical produces confident wrong answers with provenance attached, so no code-vertical NL deployment claim may rest on the front-end's fail-closed contract until a successor repairs the frame direction stage and re-clears the S2 gate."
