docs/next/a5-llm-refute-adjudication.md:125:- [EXTRAPOLATION — honest cost] What is genuinely lost: **any scale-trend statement from a5-llm.** And what survives must be stated NARROWLY: a5-llm is a marginal-inference-cost SUBSTRATE comparison — a deterministic engine answering formal, self-authored queries against its own extracted typed store, versus pinned small LLMs on the same slice. On that slice the engine beats every pinned small-LLM cell by ≥0.46 conjunctive accuracy even under the harshest row-handling reading (≥0.577 complete-case; 0.660 as-logged) at >2×10⁴ lower marginal $/query. It is NOT verifier-offload evidence generally: there is no NL boundary (the NL leg is separately measured — a5-nl, FAIL), no conventional typed-store/checker control arm, no all-in authoring/indexing cost accounting, no deployable-RAG claim, and no evidence of kernel usefulness to a model. It is narrow evidence for cheap deterministic execution on the measured slice; a SIGN at R1–R3 SmolLM2 only; no claim the gap grows/shrinks with scale, no slope law, no extrapolation past 1.7B. That was already the envelope's position; Defect 2 means one verdict field (and one report line) said otherwise. Three audits now exist (§0b), and every one of them independently recomputed the verdict-bearing numbers to full float precision — once remediated, those adversarial recomputes are the strongest replication a5-llm has.
