registry/assessments/a5-llm.json:38:      "[MEASURED, audit-recomputed endpoints; record MEASURED-UNAUDITED] HA5-LLM at exactly this scope: on the pinned 977-query kot-query-code/1 slice the deterministic kot-axiom engine scored conj 1.0 (855/855 covered-exact under STRICT a5 rules incl. provenance+license; 122/122 controls refused with the exact expected ERR codes) vs best gate-valid LLM cell llm-rag-R3 conj 0.3398 under everything-pro-LLM lenient scoring (ASM-0012); absolute effect +0.6602, one-sided 95% BCa LB +0.6346, 6.3x the 0.10 margin. The arXiv:2505.12118 motivation converts LIT-BACKED -> MEASURED on this slice at R1-R3.",
registry/assessments/a5-llm.json:46:      "[DESIGN-BOUND — the substrate confound, GPT-5.6 G5, ENDORSED] The honest ceiling of this record: 'a deterministic engine over its own extracted, typed records beats a small closed-book-or-RAG LLM, by a wide margin and at >=10^4x lower marginal inference cost, on a self-authored oracle-favourable code slice whose queries are already formal.' The inputs are formal kot-query-code/1 objects — no NL, no parse step — and there is NO conventional-substrate arm (SQL/Datalog/AST-index over the same records, or LLM-emits-kot-query/1-engine-executes). Nothing in this evidence distinguishes the kot-axiom kernel machinery from ANY typed store plus deterministic checker; the content-vs-substrate question is open by construction. This PASS is a substrate comparison and must be narrated as one — not as a kernel-superiority result, not as a deployment differentiator. The deployment-shaped comparisons live in the pre-registered successors (l3a-parse for the NL/parse leg; the e9 structured-null arm for kernel-vs-any-schema).",
registry/assessments/a5-llm.json:47:      "[ENVELOPE-BOUND, verbatim scope] One model family, one vendor, 3 rungs 135M-1.7B => SIGN plus at most direction/order-of-magnitude language, never a slope law (the verdict object's mechanical scale_language_licensed='slope' is OVERRIDDEN by the binding envelope verbatim — and the separation gate failure independently voids scale language for the direct column). No frontier or long-context claim; no deployable-RAG effectiveness claim (the null is oracle-strong BY DESIGN and says nothing about real retrieval); no NL behaviour (a5-nl); no static-analysis-from-source claim (no such arm); no statement about kernel usefulness to any model's internal computation. Covered-by-construction: the 977 queries were authored against the extracted records — no representativeness for any other codebase, language, or query distribution.",
registry/assessments/a5-llm.json:52:      "[BINDING-NOTE — ASM-0012 vs GPT-5.6 item 5, RECONCILED] No contradiction, by direction: ASM-0012 stipulates the pro-LLM-lenient instrument is CONSERVATIVE for engine-superiority readings — true, and that is the direction that realized. GPT-5.6 correctly identifies the same leniency as ANTI-CONSERVATIVE for the differentiator-KILL direction (a vague-answer-accepting extractor could falsely place an LLM cell within 0.05). That failure mode had no purchase here: the kill did not fire and is 0.41 absolute out of reach even under the joint worst-case leniency+truncation repair bound (0.538 vs window 0.95). HOWEVER: had the kill fired, this record's instrument could NOT have validated it — a fired kill under a lenient-only extractor is uninterpretable. Binding on successors (a5-llm-frontier, a5-nl, l3a-cost, any record whose kill could plausibly fire): adopt the extractor sensitivity/specificity gate against blinded labels with unparsed-counted-wrong (GPT-5.6 G5(ii)) BEFORE freeze. Adopting it into a5-llm now is unlawful (frozen, run, unblinded — see the correction record) and unnecessary (the direction it protects did not realize)."
